verses.text:
These are the ways of all who gain their riches through theft and deceit; 
\q2 the things they stole destroy the lives of the thieves who cling to them. 
\q1

Wisdom will fill your life; 
\q2 knowing what Yahweh wants you to know will cause you to be joyful.
\q1

Put all your trust in Yahweh,
\q2 and do not take action because you made up your mind what you should do; 
\q1

When you gain money, honor Yahweh by giving him the tithe;
\q2 give him the first portion of what you received, to remember it all came from him. 
\q1

for Yahweh only corrects those he loves,
\q2 just like parents correct their children whom they love.
\q1

Those who get wisdom are fortunate;
\q1 with her they also get understanding.
\q1

Wisdom can make you able to live a long life, if you do what she teaches; 
\q2 she is also ready to make you wealthy and to persuade other people to honor you.
\q1

When you have attained wisdom, it will be like a beautiful wreath of honor on your head;
\q2 she will give you a beautiful crown."
\q1

Do not do what wicked people do, nor be with them;
\q1 do not be with people who do evil things. 
\q1

Stay far from those ways;
\q2 turn another way and go on another road. 
\q1

They get their strength, and they are fed by doing what is wrong;
\q and they are intoxicated by hurting others; they get drunk on it.
\q1

Protect your heart with all your strength and guard what you love;
\q2 guard it, for it becomes a fountain overflowing with life. 
\q1

Make it your aim to keep any lying speech, any deceptive talk away from you; 
\q2 and put away from you anything that might corrode their values or harm them with useless talk. 
\q1

Take care about where you will go, and take care to be sure that the way is safe;
\q2 then you will know what to expect along the way.
\q1

She walks down to the place of death;
\q2 if you follow her, she will lead you all the way to the grave. 
\q1

Stay far away from the immoral woman;
\q2 do not go near the door of her house. 
\q1

Then you will say, "I hated it when I was punished for doing wrong; 
\q2 I despised people when they told me how to live. 
\q1

I was almost destroyed by bad things that happened to me;
\q2 and this was known to everyone who came together to worship Yahweh."
\q1

May your fountain be blessed;
\q1 may you be happy with the woman you married when you were young.
\q

An evil person's sinful desires take hold of him; 
\q2 his sins are like a trap that catches him. 
\q1

The one who does bad things lays out plans within himself;
\q2 he stirs up constant conflict wherever he goes. 
\q1

His own disaster will overtake him in a second;
\q2 he will be crushed to the point that he cannot be healed. 
\q1

Keep these lessons and tie them close inside as a part of yourself;
\q2 tie them around your neck, to remind you how important they are to you.
\q1

Do not throw your desires after such a woman, nor should you desire her beauty;
\q do not let her capture you by the way she looks at you.
\q1

Wounds and shame will come to him;
\q1 he will never forget how others disgraced him for his deed.
\q1

Tie my commands to your fingers to remind you; 
\q2 write them on a tablet, like Moses wrote the law, in your inner self. 
\q1

she searches for a man as she walks along the streets one day, and another day she stands to find a man in the market;
\q2 at every street corner she waits to trap a man.
\q1

My husband is not at home;
\q2 he has gone away on a long journey.
\q1

He filled a bag with money and took it with him; 
\q2 he will not come back until the middle of the month."
\q1

So she she convinces him with her persuasive words;
\q2 because of her smooth and convincing talk, he gives in to what she wants to do.
\q1

She has caused many men to be ruined;
\q2 truly, no one can count the men she destroyed—they are too many to count.
\q1

"I am calling out to everyone; 
\q2 I am shouting to all people!
\q1

You people who have no training, you must be taught how to live;
\q2 you must learn so that you can understand completely.
\q1

for I speak what is true;
\q2 I detest evil things so much, I hate to even speak about them.
\q1

Everything that I say is right;
\q2 I do not say anything that changes the meaning of what is good or that leads people away from it. 
\q1

My words give good advice to the one who understands the meaning of what I say;
\q2 my words are are right for those who have learned to tell what is good from what is evil.
\q1

For I, Wisdom, am more precious than jewels;
\q2 nothing you desire is as valuable as I am.
\q1

I give good advice and I have the best wisdom; 
\q2 I have true understanding about the nature of things, and I have great strength.
\q1

When kings are wise, they rule well;
\q2 and when rulers are wise, they make laws that are just.
\q1

By me, Wisdom, rulers govern their people;
\q by me those who have authority guide their people with justice.
\q1

I am Wisdom, and I love all who love me;
\q2 those who work hard to find me will find me.
\q1

Yahweh created me, Wisdom; he made me when he began to create the world;
\q2 I was the first thing he created in the beginning.
\q1

I was at Yahweh's side as his master craftsman;
\q1 I made him happy every day, and I always rejoiced when I was with him.
\q1

I was delighted with the whole world he created;
\q2 I was happy with the people he brought into existence, too.
\q1

A foolish woman talks loudly;
\q2 she is untaught in the subjects of wisdom and she knows very little.
\q1

Riches that you got by being dishonest will not have any value;
\q2 but when you do what is right, you will be protected from death. 
\q1

A lazy person who will not work becomes poor;
\q2 those who work hard become rich.
\q1

He is wise who harvests the crops when they are ready to be gathered;
\q2 but it would be shameful for him to sleep while others are harvesting the crop. 
\q1

Those who do right will receive many good gifts from God; 
\q2 but those who do wicked things cover their violence so they cannot be seen. 
\q1

When we remember those who do what is right, we get a blessing from Yahweh; 
\q2 but we cannot remember the names of the wicked. 
\q1

An honest person lives his life and has nothing to hide;
\q2 but one who is dishonest—his lies will be discovered. 
\q1

A person who does right is like a spring that gives life-saving water;
\q2 but the wicked person hides his brutality by his words. 
\q1

Hatred has the power to start many arguments; 
\q but love covers anything that may hurt us. 
\q1

Life can be found by the one who is trained by discipline;
\q2 but the one who will not listen to correction wanders away.
\q1

When people talk a lot, sin is sure to follow;
\q2 if you are wise, you will always be careful about what you say.
\q1

What the wicked fear will happen to them;
\q1 those who do what is right will get what they hoped for.
\q1

If you give Yahweh the respect he deserves, you will live for a long time;
\q2 but wicked people die before they become old.
\q1

Following Yahweh brings protection to those who keep their promises;
\q2 but those who do not follow him find out he destroys those who do what is evil.
\q1

When people use scales that are not correct; 
\q1 Yahweh is angry that they are stealing from their customers;
\q2 he is delighted with those who use correct weights on the scales.
\q1

People who are proud live in such a way that always ends in disgrace;
\q2 people who are humble are the only ones who can learn about wisdom.
\q1

People who keep their promises also make choices that lead them in the right way;
\q2 those who cannot be trusted are destroyed by their own dishonesty. 
\q1

Your money will not help you on the day Yahweh judges the world;
\q2 but if you do what is right, you will be kept safe from many dangers, even death.
\q1

When people are honest and good, they know where they should go and what they should do;
\q2 but those who do evil find that their wickedness will destroy them.
\q1

When a wicked person dies, all he hoped for in the future is lost;
\q2 what he wanted to accomplish with his strength, will never happen. 
\q1

The one who does what is right, Yahweh delivers from trouble; 
\q2 and Yahweh gives that trouble to the wicked. 
\q1

A person who has no kind of religious faith uses his words to destroy his neighbor;
\q2 but people who do right will be saved by the knowledge they have gathered.
\q1

When there are people in the city who please God and they give good gifts to others, the city becomes great;
\q2 but the words spoken by the wicked tear down the city. 
\q1

The one who treats his friend with contempt has no good judgment; 
\q2 a person who has learned what is important says nothing.
\q1

A nation will be destroyed if it does not have leaders who guide it wisely;
\q2 but the nation will have victory when it listens to many advisors.
\q1

A kindhearted woman earns respect;
\q2 but violent people take hold of riches.
\q1

If a person sows seed, he can expect to harvest a crop; 
\q1 his few seeds will give him much more;
\q1 another person does not plant a crop, and he becomes poor.
\q1

Those who give generously to others will prosper;
\q2 if you share your water with other people, you will have enough for yourself, too. 
\q1

What wicked people say is like setting up a secret attack while planning to commit murder;
\q2 but when those who please Yahweh speak, their words keep them out of danger.
\q1

A person will be praised according to how much widsom he has;
\q2 but one who takes good things and twists them into bad will be hated.
\q1

Foolish people think that what they are doing is always right;
\q2 but wise people are willing to listen to advice.
\q1

A foolish person quickly shows how angry he is;
\q2 but those who have good sense ignore it when someone insults them.
\q1

When a person speaks without thinking, it is like they are taking stabs at you with a sword; 
\q2 but what wise people say helps to heal the hurts.
\q1

When evil is planned there must be lies within those who carry it out;
\q2 but those who give advice that leads to peace, those advisors will celebrate.
\q1

A wise child pays attention to the teaching his father gives him;
\q2 but a stubborn child refuses to listen to correction. 
\q1

The person who is very careful about what he says preserves his life;
\q2 the one who talks too much ruins everything.
\q1

Some people have many possessions, but they have nothing of value;
\q2 but other people give all they have away, and yet have the best kind of riches.
\q1

People who think too much of themselves will spend all their money; 
\q2 the one who makes his money by working with his hands, will find ways to make his money grow.
\q1

Those who have good sense always take action from what they know is true;
\q2 a foolish person proves his decisions are folly, and everyone sees it.
\q1

The one who honors Yahweh in the way he lives, gives to Yahweh the respect he deserves; 
\q2 the dishonest person shows his disrespect, and he despises Yahweh. 
\q1

Pride grows out of the mouth of the fool, like an offshoot from a tree; 
\q2 but what wise people say preserves their lives. 
\q1

Where there are no cattle feeding in the barn, the feeding trough is clean; 
\q2 but if a farmer only has one ox, still he can grow a very great crop.
\q1

A person keeps close inside all his bitterness and disappointment; 
\q2 and no stranger will ever know all the joy it contains. 
\q1

The faithless man will receive from Yahweh what he deserves; 
\q2 but Yahweh will give a good person what is his.
\q1

A wise person sees evil and is afraid of it, and he turns away from it; 
\q2 the foolish person boldly throws aside every warning. 
\q1

Those who have not been instructed have foolishness handed to them;
\q2 those who have learned a little knowledge are surrounded by it. 
\q1

A witness who tells the truth, saves the lives of the innocent; 
\q2 a lying witness is filled with deceit. 
\q1

When wise people speak, they give praise to the value of knowledge; 
\q2 foolish people continually say foolish things.
\q1

A person who can give healing with what they say is like a tree that gives life;
\q2 when someone lies to you, it can feel like they have crushed you.
\q1

The people who do right think carefully before they answer;
\q2 it is like the wicked pour out of their mouths all kinds of evil when they talk.
\q1

In a king's smile there is life;
\q2 when he is happy, he is like the cloud that brings the spring rain.
\q1

When you understand, it is as if you have found a fountain of life within you; 
\q2 but fools find their punishment when their foolishness comes back to them. 
\q1

From deep within him, the wise person speaks from the insight he has learned; 
\q2 and so when he speaks he has the power to pursuade others.
\q1

The one who is slow to get angry is stronger than a warrior;
\q2 the one who is self-controlled is mightier than one who conquers a city by force. 
\q1

A fool is not able to give an eloquent speech;
\q2 even more is it wrong to lie to someone with a royal title.
\q1

An evil person is only interested in disobeying the rules;
\q2 he deserves a messenger who will be cruel to him. 
\q1

Starting a quarrel is like pumping water and letting it run everywhere;
\q2 it is much better to walk away before it starts.
\q1

The one who loves to have arguments, that person also loves the sin that lies behind the conflict;
\q2 one thing leads to another: the one who makes the threshold of his door too high, it is sure to make someone break the bones in his foot.
\q1

A foolish person says things that start arguments;
\q2 he says things that make other people want to beat him with a stick.
\q1

A foolish person brings himself to ruin by the things he says;
\q2 his very words set a trap in which he will be caught. 
\q1

The name of Yahweh is like a castle that can never be overrun;
\q2 those who do what is right run for safety into it, and in the fortress of his name, they are safe. 
\q1

The wealthy person depends on his wealth as a city depends on its fortifications;
\q2 he thinks it protects him as well as a high wall.
\q1

One person says that he has many friends, but his life is ruined by them; 
\q2 but there is a friend who stands with us through everything,
\q2 and he is always close at our side, even closer than a brother.

All the brothers of one who is poor hate him; 
\q2 and even more do his friends hate him, and they go far away from him; 
\q2 he calls out to them, but they have left. 
\q1

The one who makes every effort to learn about wisdom, loves himself; 
\q2 having understanding helps you know what is good and what is not. 
\q1

Train your children and give them discipline while it is still possible to rescue them;
\q2 but do not allow them to offend you so much that you consider taking their lives.
\q1

A hot-tempered person will pay a price for his anger; 
\q2 if you rescue him after he had has an outburst, you will have to do it again and again. 
\q1

The lazy person puts his hand in the dish;
\q2 he is not able to raise his hand up to his mouth to eat. 
\q1

If you love to sleep all the time, you will become poor;
\q2 stay awake when you should be at work and you will have plenty to eat. 
\q1

A king who is wise will separate the wicked from among his people;
\q2 then he will drive a threshing cart over their bodies to kill them. 
\q1

Love and faithfulness preserve the life of the king; 
\q2 his throne is made strong by steadfast love. 
\q1

Give a gift to a person who is angry with you, and it may turn away his anger; 
\q2 a secret gift may help a person who is angry at you to calm down.
\q1

Love pleasure and it will make you poor;
\q2 you cannot be rich and love to drink wine and eat expensive foods. 
\q1

The things that the lazy person chooses to do will kill him;
\q2 he refuses to work. 
\q1

Now listen to what those who are wise have said;
\q2 give it all your attention and learn the knowledge you will need if you are to become wise. 
\q1

I have written thirty of these sayings for you to learn; 
\q2 sayings to give you advice and to teach you what you do not know. 
\q1

for Yahweh stands to defend them, 
\q2 and he will take the life of those who stole from the poor. 
\q1

Do not crave the special and expensive food the ruler enjoys;
\q2 the food will deceive you.
\q1

Do not work so much that you are always tired, so you can become rich;
\q2 be wise and know when you should stop and rest. 
\q1

When you realize what he is really thinking, you will want to vomit what you have eaten;
\q2 and you will have wasted all the compliments you gave about the fine meal he prepared. 
\q1

Do not waste time talking to a fool;
\q2 he will only despise the wise things that you say.
\q1

Again, do not remove the ancient boundary stone. It is a marker for the property lines;
\q2 and do not claim land that is set apart for orphans to work, 
\q1

Do not refuse to discipline your children;
\q2 if you punish them, they will not die,
\q1

Do not envy sinful people;
\q2 but give Yahweh the respect he deserves, all day long. 
\q1

because drunkards and gluttons will become poor;
\q2 and they will sleep so much that they will have nothing but rags to wear.
\q1

When you study wisdom, think of it as buying truth, but never selling it; 
\q2 and the same for wisdom, and with discipline, and also with understanding; 
\q2 let it be as though you were buying them so you can keep them for the rest of your life. 
\q1

The father of a child who does what is right will be very happy; 
\q2 any man who has a wise son will be very happy because of him.
\q1

A prostitute is like a very deep pit, that is easy to fall into, but difficult to get out; 
\q2 another man's wife is a narrow pit; just as dangerous as a deep pit, but of a different kind. 
\q1

The immoral woman is waiting for you, waiting like a robber waits for his victim; 
\q2 and they cause many men to become liars and traitors to those who love them.
\q1

You will think you are on a ship that is tossing on the sea;
\q2 you will be like someone who is trying to sleep up on the rigging of the boat.
\q1

Do not want what evil people have;
\q2 do not desire them for friends,
\q1

because they are plotting to do violence;
\q2 they talk about making trouble.
\q1

for with wise guidance you can wage a war successfully, 
\q2 and by the advice of many advisors there will be victory.
\q1

Wisdom is something that a fool cannot understand;
\q2 at the gate where the elders gather, the fool has nothing to say. 
\q1

A foolish plan is not only folly, it is sin; 
\q2 when people tell the truth, they hate those who are conceited and mock everyone.
\q1

Rescue the ones who are being carried away to the slaughter;
\q2 they stagger and fall—hold them back from the one who would kill them.
\q1

My son, eat honey, because it tastes good;
\q2 the honeycomb is sweet.
\q1

for Yahweh will see how you treat your enemy, and if he disapproves how you treat him,
\q1 Yahweh may turn his wrath from your enemy and put it on you. 
\q1

for there is no future for the wicked;
\q2 they are like a lamp whose light will soon be put out.
\q1

My son, give to Yahweh and give to the king the respect each of them deserves,
\q2 and do not associate with anyone who rebels against either Yahweh or the king; 
\q1

Do not say, "I will do to him what he did to me;
\q2 I will pay him back for what he did to me."
\q1

What kings think is above the way peasants think; they are like the heavens, they are above us all; 
\q2 and all kings have the same deep burdens that others cannot understand. 
\q1

Silver cannot be used by the metal worker, 
\q2 unless the silver is heated and dross is removed from it;
\q1

If you and your neighbor are having a disagreement, 
\q2 settle it between yourselves, and do not tell others any secret you have learned about; 
\q1

for others might find out what you have done, 
\q2 and you would be ashamed; 
\q2 and from that time on, you will have a bad reputation.
\q1

Use the right words and a phrase put together to say exactly what you mean;
\q2 this is as delightful as seeing designs of gold in a silver bowl.
\q1

Do not go to your neighbor's house too often;
\q2 he may get tired of you, and if you do not stop, he could even grow to hate you. 
\q1

If your enemies are hungry, give them something to eat;
\q2 if they are thirsty, give them something to drink;
\q1

When wind blows from the north, it will certainly rain;
\q2 it is just as certain that someone who tells secrets about others will make people angry.
\q1

It is not good to eat too much honey;
\q2 that is like searching for more honor when you already have honor.
\q1

The fire goes out when there is no more wood to burn; 
\q2 and so arguments stop when no one is gossipping.
\q1

As charcoal can ignite into burning coal and a log of wood into a fire;
\q2 so the one who argues sets anger ablaze. 
\q1

The gossip tells stories that are like sweet treats to eat; 
\q2 people eat them like candy until they are filled. 
\q1

The one who is filled with hate, by the words he speaks, he hides his true feelings;
\q2 and he stores up more and more lies within himself.
\q1

One who digs a pit will fall into it; 
\q2 and a stone rolls back on the one who tried to push it up a hill. 
\q1

When a person is walking along and he has a full stomach, he may step on a honeycomb because he is not hungry;
\q2 but if he were very hungry, even bitter things would taste sweet to him.
\q1

The aroma of perfume and the scent of incense can help to make a person feel happy;
\q2 but the sweetness of a friend is more important than his advice. 
\q1

A wife who continually argues with her husband is as annoying as 
\q2 the constant dripping of water on a rainy day;
\q1

When a person looks in the water, he sees his own face;
\q2 similarly when we look at what a person loves, we know what he is like deep inside.
\q1

You know that the Place of the Dead and The Destroyer are never satisfied;
\q2 and people, too, are never satisfied and always want more. 
\q1

The grass dies out and then the new growth starts to grow;
\q2 and on the mountains food for the cattle is stacked up in the barns. 
\q1

The more sin there is in a country, the greater the number of rulers it will have; 
\q2 but when there is a ruler who has understanding and knowledge, the country can last a long time. 
\q1

Those who reject the law are the same people who speak well of those who are wicked;
\q2 but those who obey the law fight against the wicked. 
\q1

The one who obeys the law is a child who has understanding of the ways of wisdom;
\q2 but if children go around with friends who are only interested in eating too much, they put their father to shame.
\q1

If you refuse to hear what the law says to you about how you should live;
\q2 then Yahweh is offended by your prayers. 
\q1

How fortunate are those who always honor Yahweh; 
\q2 but those who refuse to listen to him, who do not want to learn from him, will fall into trouble.
\q1

You know what a roaring lion or a charging bear is like; 
\q2 they are just like the wicked ruler who is tearing apart poor people. 
\q1

When a person lives his life and is blameless, Yahweh will keep him safe;
\q2 but one who lives by his lies will be suddenly ruined.
\q1

A farmer who works his field will have plenty of food to eat;
\q2 but anyone who gives his time to worthless dreams, will be very poor. 
\q1

Yahweh will give good things to a faithful person; 
\q2 but he will certainly punish those who become rich quickly.
\q1

It is bad to give a favor to one person and not to another;
\q2 some people will do what is wrong just to get a piece of bread.
\q1

A son who desires to learn about wisdom makes his father very happy;
\q2 but the son who is a companion of prostitutes will lose all his money
\q1

A bad person sets a trap with his sin; then he falls into it; 
\q2 but one who does right is full of songs and joy.
\q1

The one who does right stands up for the poor and defends them; 
\q2 but wicked people do not see the importance of standing up for the poor. 
\q1

People who sneer and mock others are like those who set a city on fire; 
\q2 but those who help people get rid of their anger are wise.
\q1

A murderer hates him who does everything right; 
\q2 and they seek to kill the one who has a good reputation.
\q1

Discipline your child and he will help you and serve you;
\q2 you will truly rejoice over him.
\q1

Any person who is proud will be humbled;
\q2 but the one who is humbled will be given honor.
\q1

A person who helps a thief, hates himself;
\q2 he overhears the curse, but he does not say anything about it. 
\q1

I have not learned about wisdom; 
\q2 I do not know Yahweh, the Holy One.
\q1

Every word of God is proven by a test that it is true;
\q2 he is like a shield that protects those who run to him.
\q1

Be careful not to add to Yahweh's words more than he has said;
\q2 if you do that, he will correct you and he will prove that you lied about what he said.
\q1

Put vain pride and lies far away from me;
\q2 and let me neither have poverty or riches, 
\q2 just give me the food I need every day.

Do not speak badly about a slave when he is standing before his master;
\q2 if you do, he will curse you, and you will be responsible; you brought it on yourself.
\q1

There are many people who curse their fathers
\q2 and they do not praise their mothers or thank them; 
\q1

These people show how proud they are in their eyes;
\q2 they make people look at them and they show their pride in their faces!
\q1

The grave, the place of the dead;
\q1 the womb of a woman that never conceived a child; 
\q1 soil that badly needs to be watered;
\q1 and a fire that burns hot and it never says, "The fire is hot enough!"
\b
\q1

There are three wonderful things I can mention; 
\q2 no, there are four that are too amazing and I cannot understand them.
\q1

the earth trembles with a slave becomes a king; 
\q1 the earth trembles when fool has eaten his food and is filled; 
\q1

Just as when you churn milk, and it produces butter,
\q2 even so, if you hit someone hard on his nose, the result is that his nose will bleed;
\q2 and, in the same way, when people are angry, they will argue and fight.

She says: You are my son; I carried you in my womb; 
\q2 you are the son, I made promises to Yahweh for you.
\q1

Do not give your strength to women;
\q2 and do not tell what your plans are, to the women who destroy kings.
\q1

Lemuel, kings should be careful about drinking wine; 
\q2 and a king should never ask, "Where is the strong drink?" 
\q1

Speak out and render judgment according to what is right; 
\q2 and plead for justice to come in the cases of the poor and the needy. 
\q1

Her children speak highly of her;
\q2 her husband also praises her.
\q1
